er than the ovarian surface.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following mutations is characteristic of high-grade Type 2 serous ovarian cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["KRAS mutations","P53 mutations","Beta-catenin mutations","CTNNB1 mutations","BRAF mutations"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHigh-grade serous ovarian cancers (Type 2) are characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003EP53\u003C/strong\u003E mutations in over 95% of cases. These aggressive cancers develop rapidly and are typically diagnosed at an advanced stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, Type 1 serous ovarian cancers are low-grade and develop gradually through a stepwise process. They commonly involve \u003Cstrong\u003EKRAS\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EBRAF\u003C/strong\u003E, and other mutations in the mitogen-activated protein kinase pathway. The \u003Cstrong\u003EBRAF\u003C/strong\u003E mutation is also associated with melanoma, colon cancer and papillary thyroid cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-catenin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECTNNB1\u003C/strong\u003E mutations are more commonly associated with endometrioid ovarian cancers rather than serous cancers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High-grade (Type 2) serous ovarian cancers are characterised by P53 mutations in over 95% of cases","Type 2 serous ovarian cancers likely originate from the fallopian tube epithelium rather than the ovarian surface","Type 1 and Type 2 serous ovarian cancers have distinct molecular pathways and mutations"],"references":["Momenimovahed Z, Tiznobaik A, Taheri S, Salehiniya H. Ovarian cancer in the world: epidemiology and risk factors. Int J Womens Health. 2019 Apr 30;11:287-299. doi: 10.2147/IJWH.S197604. PMID: 31118829; PMCID: PMC6500433","Cho KR, Shih IeM. Ovarian cancer. Annu Rev Pathol. 2009;4:287-313. doi: 10.1146/annurev.pathol.4.110807.092246. PMID: 18842102; PMCID: PMC2679364","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15731"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56972"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:09:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:09:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attr